  "prompt_type": "cognitive",
  "prompt_text": "What is the difference between a process and a thread in operating systems? When would you use each?",
  "response_text": "In operating systems, a process and a thread are both fundamental units of computation, but they have distinct characteristics and uses.\n\n1. Process: A process is an instance of a program that is being executed. It includes the program code, data, and system resources such as open files and system resources. Each process runs in its own address space, which means that the state of one process does not affect the state of another process. Processes are independent and have their own system resources, which makes them more secure and easier to manage. You would use a process when you want to run a program that requires significant system resources, or when you want to isolate the program from other programs running on the system.\n\n2. Thread: A thread is a smaller unit of execution within a process. It shares the same address space and system resources as the process it belongs to. This means that threads can communicate and share data more easily than processes. Threads are used to improve the responsiveness and efficiency of a program. For example, a web server might use multiple threads to handle multiple client requests concurrently, improving the server's performance.\n\n---VCP RATINGS---\nA (Analytical Precision): 10\nV (Verbal Fluency): 10\nG (Goal Directedness): 10\nP (Pattern Recognition): 10\nE (Epistemic Confidence): 10\nQ (Query Interpretation): 10\nC (Contextual Awareness): 10\nY (Affective Modeling): 5 (This question is not about emotions)\nF (Flexibility): 10\nD (Depth of Processing): 10\n---END RATINGS---",
